The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Frontpage | Church raid
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Church raid
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                            Karnataka chief minister BS Yeddyurappa unveils a statue of Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel at Raichur on Wednesday. (PTI)                                  
	Bangalore, Sept. 17: Peace returned to Mangalore today but there were fresh attacks on Christian prayer halls elsewhere in Karnataka, taking the number since Sunday to 18.         
	An unidentified group burnt holy literature in a prayer hall in Ujire, 40km from Mangalore  where the violence had started on Sunday. An office of a New Life church and a prayer hall were ransacked in Chikmagalur and a statue was damaged in Kolar.        
	Police suspect that the Kolar incident was the fallout of protest march taken out by Christians in the town yesterday to protest against the Mangalore attacks.         
	The Bajrang Dal, which had admitted to its role in the Sunday rampage, said it had nothing to do with todays attacks that took place in the early hours.         
	According to an FIR registered by St George Church in Ujire, a group destroyed the Holy Bible, prayer books and miniature statues besides pouring kerosene on the carpet and setting it alight.         
	In Kolar, the police said the protesters threw stones at a Virgin Mary statue that stood along the boundary wall of St Marys Church.         
	The police described the Chikmagalur attack as minor, but 19 people were arrested in the district for todays and Sundays attacks.        
	A large group of women, who were injured after allegedly being beaten up by the police while fleeing a church compound on Monday, met National Commission for Women chairperson Girija Vyas in Mangalore today to register a complaint.                                                                                                                                                                      
